	<div class="blog-archive-entries-wrapper">
		<div id="unique-entry-id-390" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">Festival of the Word</h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Friday, 25 February 2011 Filed in: <span class="blog-entry-category"><a href="category-justin-somper.php">Justin Somper</a></span><span class="blog-entry-category"> <a href="category-events.php">Events</a></span></div><div class="blog-entry-body"><div class="image-left"><img class="imageStyle" alt="vampirates" src="vampirates.jpg" width="40" height="40" /></div>Justin Somper will be attending the OsLitFest on Wednesday 16th March from 3.15-4.30pm at Oswestry Library Arthur St Oswestry, SY11 1JN.  I love the description of the cost "Cost: Free to enjoy - just pop-in to meet Justin."<br /><br />"Justin will be appearing at The Marches School earlier in the day to read and speak with students.  Then, afterwards, come along and meet the author of these well-liked books at Oswestry Library, and even get your book-signed too!"<br /><br />Books must be getting popular again as there seem to be more and more literary festivals or as Oswestry puts it "Festival of the Word".<br />Please see <a href="http://www.thebestof.co.uk/local/oswestry/events/285029/justin-somper-author-of-vampirates" rel="self" title="http://www.thebestof.co.uk/local/oswestry/events/285029/justin-somper-author-of-vampirates">http://www.thebestof.co.uk/local/oswestry/events/285029/justin-somper-author-of-vampirates</a> for more information.<br /></div></div><div id="unique-entry-id-389" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">Charities</h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Wednesday, 16 February 2011 Filed in: <span class="blog-entry-category"><a href="category-books.php">Books</a></span><span class="blog-entry-category"> <a href="category-pirates.php">Pirates</a></span></div><div class="blog-entry-body"><div class="image-left"><img class="imageStyle" alt="Captain Conk" src="Sq_RND.jpg" width="40" height="40" /></div>I have heard recently of two charities that might interest you.<br /><br />The first is a UK one with a pirate.  For anyone who does not know Comic Relief has announced the next Red Nose Day will be 18th March 2011 and one of the noses they have released is Captain Conk the pirate.  Every two years the UK comedians help raise money to help make a difference to peoples lives both in the UK and abroad (predominantly in Africa).  So for the &pound;1 spent to buy either a Captain Conk red nose from Sainsbury's or Captain Conk pen from Ryman's, half of the profits goes to UK and half to Africa.  (Just a note on the nose boxes it says "with at least 70p going to Comic Relief" and the pens have "Ryman will donate &pound;1 for each pen sold.")<br />Please see <a href="http://www.rednoseday.com/" rel="self" title="http://www.rednoseday.com/">http://www.rednoseday.com/</a> for more information.<br /><br />The second is from the United States with books.  I heard about it via Twitter<br />"RT @<a href="http://twitter.com/iEatWordsTweets" rel="self" title="http://twitter.com/iEatWordsTweets">iEatWordsTweets</a>: @<a href="http://twitter.com/cassieclare" rel="self" title="http://twitter.com/cassieclare">cassieclare</a> Hi Cassie! Would you please help us raise awareness for our Books for Kids charity? <a href="http://bit.ly/e8ACRT" rel="self" title="http://bit.ly/e8ACRT">http://bit.ly/e8ACRT</a>"<br />The Phoenix Children's Hospital and Scottish Rite Hospital for terminally ill children are asking for help towards buying brand new books for children.<br />Please see <a href="http://www.ieatwords.net/2011/02/books-for-kids-lets-give-back.html" rel="self" title="http://www.ieatwords.net/2011/02/books-for-kids-lets-give-back.html">http://www.ieatwords.net/2011/02/books-for-kids-lets-give-back.html</a> for more information.<br /></div></div><div id="unique-entry-id-388" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">Libraries</h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Saturday, 12 February 2011 Filed in: <span class="blog-entry-category"><a href="category-books.php">Books</a></span></div><div class="blog-entry-body"><div class="image-left"><img class="imageStyle" alt="books" src="books.jpg" width="42" height="40" /></div>As well as authors like Justin Somper getting behind libraries, it looks like school children are too.  Please see the article on the front of first news, <a href="http://www.firstnews.co.uk/news/schoolgirl-asks-david-cameron-to-save-our-libraries-i3532" rel="self" title="http://www.firstnews.co.uk/news/schoolgirl-asks-david-cameron-to-save-our-libraries-i3532">http://www.firstnews.co.uk/news/schoolgirl-asks-david-cameron-to-save-our-libraries-i3532</a> .   (I noticed Miss Trueman in the article is holding up the Lemonade War.  My son read this recently and loved it.)<br /><br />It made me realise in the two months I have been back in England I have been down the library twice.  First to get my card and second to use the internet.  I thought about why and realised the two local branches are not as accessible (to me) as they first look.  The first is in the local town, which when you can find a parking space near the library charges you 70p an hour.<br /><br />The second is in the local secondary school, I am not sure where.  My issue with that is; I get nervous the first couple of times going into a new school.  Yes I am an adult, yes I walk my kids into school every day, yes when my son was small I helped lesson to people in his class reading, yes I know reading is important and I should be encouraging my kids, but the truth is I think on my kids first day in their new schools I am more scared than them.  Having learning difficulties made school hard and Dyslexia was not understood 35 years ago as it is today.  I was labelled lazy and kept in at break times.  Going places like a strange school is scary especially alone so I have sub-continuously not planed to go to the library.<br /><br />But were I last lived the library was in the corner of the local sports centre and had free parking.  We visited as a family every two weeks.  They had a website and encouraged people to go via the website to select your books in advance, then collect them within a week from the hold shelf.  Thus encouraging people to read whole sets of books not just from the local branch but any book listed on the library catalogue.<br /><br />Also in my kids last schools, (one went to the school on the left and the other went to the school on the right), every autumn/fall term, every class made a trip to the local library and every child was expected to have their library card sent into school in advance (or a form completed to get one).<br /><br />Before that I lived in a village between two towns.  The kids used to walk to school (unlike here) and the local library was between two of the local schools.  So it was easy to take a slight detour home via the library.<br /><br />It is weird how, where somewhere is placed and social attitudes affects your habits.  So good luck with the save the libraries campaign.<br /><br /><h5>Comments Back</h5><br />As most people who travel by train regularly read, why don't libraries arrange collection from BR's coffee shops (after ordering online) and have return boxes inside the same shops.  Most stations have 15 minutes free parking outside too.<br /></div></div><div id="unique-entry-id-387" class="blog-entry"><h1 class="blog-entry-title">Hornsey Library in Crouch End</h1><div class="blog-entry-date">Tuesday, 01 February 2011 Filed in: <span class="blog-entry-category"><a href="category-justin-somper.php">Justin Somper</a></span></div><div class="blog-entry-body"><div class="image-left"><img class="imageStyle" alt="vampirates" src="vampirates.jpg" width="40" height="40" /></div>Justin Somper wrote on twitter that "Next Saturday (Feb 5th) I'll be at Hornsey Library in Crouch End at 2:00 pm to chat and mark National Library Day. Come and say hi!"<br /><br />Sadly I will not be able to make is as it coincides with Chinese New Year celebrations, I hope Cheng Li approves me celebrating the year of the Rabbit instead.<br /></div></div>
	</div>
	
	 
